Beneventum] The Appia Vi». took a north-east turn from Caudium for eleven or twelve miles till it came to Beneventum (Benevento), a very ancient town, by tra- dition said to have been founded by Dio- medes, and the name of which was ori· ginally, when the Samnites had it, Maleven- tum, or some name that sounded so like Maleventum to a Latin ear that the Romans thought fit to change it (for good luck) to Beneventum. In no town but Rome are there so many ancient remains as in Benevento. Nearly all the walls are built of altars, tombs, columns, &c- ς and the arch of Trajan, erected probably in com- memoration of his construction of the roaael from Beneventum to Brundusium (since the same year, Aa). 114, appears on the arch that is found on the milliary co· lumns along the read), still remains in pretty good preservation.
